    <p class="ch-sub">How a single thought becomes a thousand</p>
    <div class="ch-div"></div>

    <p class="lead">It was two in the morning. The room was dark and completely quiet. And yet somehow — impossibly — my mind was the loudest it had been all day.</p>

    <div class="story">
      <p>Rohan had been lying in bed for forty minutes. Not tossing and turning dramatically the way people do in films. Just lying there, still, eyes open, staring at the ceiling while his brain ran a full audit of every mistake he had made in the past six months.</p>
      <p>It had started simple enough. He'd sent a message to his manager earlier that day — a project update — and somewhere between pressing send and dinner, he became convinced the tone had been wrong. Too casual. Or maybe too formal.</p>
      <p>And from that single seed, the mind had bloomed into something enormous. By midnight, he was no longer thinking about the message. He was re-examining his entire career, his personality, whether he was fundamentally unlikable, and at one point — he wasn't sure how he got there — whether he had made the right choices in his twenties at all.</p>
      <p>At 2 a.m., he was twenty-eight years old and he was already rewriting his life story. He hadn't moved in forty minutes.</p>
    </div>

    <p>If you have lived inside a human body for any length of time, you know exactly what Rohan was experiencing. Maybe your version sounds like replaying arguments from relationships that ended years ago. Or a mental slideshow of worst-case scenarios before every important meeting. Or a persistent, low-level hum of inadequacy that doesn't say anything specific — it just hums.</p>

    <p>The name for all of this is overthinking. But that word has been used so casually that it has started to feel like a personality trait rather than a problem. We say <em>"I'm an overthinker"</em> the way we say <em>"I'm a morning person"</em> — as if it's simply who we are, fixed and permanent.</p>

    <p><strong>It is not who you are.</strong> It is something that happens to you — and more importantly, something you can change your relationship with.</p>

    <div class="pull-quote">
      <p>The mind is not your enemy. It is simply untrained. And an untrained mind, left to its own devices, will run the same circuits until something breaks — or until someone decides to learn how it actually works.</p>
      <cite>— InnerVirtueX</cite>
