        <div class="story">
          <p>Priya used to think she just had a lot going on. She was managing a team of eleven people, raising a seven-year-old mostly alone after her divorce, and taking care of her mother. But when she started paying attention — really paying attention — she discovered something startling.</p>
          <p>For every one hour of actual difficult activity, there were three or four hours of mental rehearsal happening in the background. Before every difficult conversation at work, she had it in her head at least six times. None of those mental rehearsals made the actual events go better. They just cost her the same energy as doing the thing itself — except they produced nothing.</p>
        </div>

        <p>This is the first important distinction this book asks you to make: <strong>the difference between thinking and spinning.</strong></p>

